<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 Sorry to harp on, but I just have to bug you about this again, Milo (especially after noticing that you are a bit of a connoiseur of 20th Century 'serious' music).<P>

 When asked about why EQ's grammar and spelling sucks so tremendously, you offered this as a reply; "It's a side effect of their being so good at
what they do." This doesn't make any sense at all as an answer -  it's like blaming bad game mechanics on the nice inventory graphics or explaining
slow frame rates by pointing to the cool names of the NPCs. That Verant doesn't see fit to hire a *writer* to do the writing is just as much an insult as
if they were to hire me to do the game box layout (I'm a graphic designer by trade), and then expect me to *also* do the 3D modeling. Hey, I've messed around in some 3D programs for a few hours, why not? I'll tell you why
not; because I *suck* at it. That I have skills in other areas does not excuse putting me in a position I am not even remotely suited for (and make no mistake, someone who doesn't know the crucial - and fairly
simple-to-grasp - difference between "Welcome my friend" and Welcome, my friend" is nowhere near qualified to be handling the language of a professional product, no matter what the medium).<P>

 So, how does Verant justify this? I can't imagine that hiring a semi-literate person to proof the text already in the game could cost even
a fifth of what they must be paying some of you IT professionals, or that it would take more than a week or two to go through it all. I'm genuinely mystified by this attitude of non-caring.<P>

 Regards, etc.<P>

 John

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   My answer makes perfect sense, because most people who live and
work in America can be expected to have had formal training in the
proper use of the English language.  Regarding your analogies, most
people have *not* had any kind of formal training in the fields of
graphics or programming.  I'm not any kind of professional writer, nor
have I ever had any kind of higher training to this effect, and yet, I
have a very good grasp of the English language, mainly because, for
whatever reasons, I sat up and paid attention in my pre-college English
and French classes (I think that taking a foreign language is very helpful
for a better understanding of one's own language), and because I like
to read.  There are hundreds of thousands, if not millions of people all
over the world who can make similar claims.<P>

   That said, I believe that it is reasonable to expect that most everyone
will manifest deficiencies in at least one area (and usually several areas)
of formal education, for any of a variety of reasons.  One of these
reasons is simple disinterest.  I've never cared much about science, so
I performed miserably in my high school biology and physics classes.
Relative to this, someone who digs computers is probably going to
excel in mathematics courses, with the possible result that his/her
English skills will fall by the wayside.  I'll still roll my eyes when
he/she
makes simple linguistic errors, but if I see that this person is highly
skilled in some field or other, I'll certainly overlook the fault.<P>

   By the way, there are two S's in "connoisseur," smart guy.<P>

