<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   I'm a big fan of comic book artist Mike Mignola.  There are few things
more impressive to me than an artist who manages to achieve both
simplicity and originality of style, and Mr. Mignola's work is some of the
simplest and yet most distinct that I've ever seen.  I think that the
angular
quality of his art would translate very well into an environment of
polygonal characters, and I'm sure that this observation of mine has
affected the way I model Rick Schmitz's EverQuest characters.  Mignola
is brilliant.<P>

   In a more abstract sense, though, there is nothing that affects my work
more than music.  Here again, simple originality (among other things) has
a profound effect on me; some musicians whom I've found particularly
fine in this regard are Steve Reich, Arvo Pärt, Cocteau Twins, Dead
Can Dance, and Seefeel.<P>

   Then there's the music of Mozart, which is probably in a class by itself.
If you've ever seen the movie _Amadeus_, there's a part near the
beginning in which Salieri states that the first few bars of one of Mozart's
works is comically simple, and yet astoundingly beautiful.  That's actually
a very good description of a lot of the composer's work.  Recently, I
was listening to the "Rex tremendae" section of his Requiem (which I do
a lot), and I was trying to figure out how he got the choir and the strings
to sound as impossibly heavenly as they do in the "qui salvandos salvas
gratis" portion.  I couldn't believe how basic the score looked -- to use
Salieri's word, it looked almost like "nothing," especially compared to
other awesome and famously complex works like Stravinsky's _Le
Sacre du Printemps_ and Schöenberg's _Fünf Orchesterstücke_.  I
can't say for certain that I seek to achieve this kind of simplicity in my
work (I doubt that I'm good enough), but I do find this kind of thing in
the works of others highly motivating.<P>

   In response to your question about viewing other works of mine, I
haven't much of anything to show anyone.  EverQuest hogs up all of
my time, and I have to struggle to do anything else (and sometimes I
have to struggle to make EQ models).  Also, I'm currently trying to
improve myself in other ways, so I don't have much time to create art,
these days.  So sorry!
<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 Milo,<P>

 Do you have a website and where can it be found? Thanks for being a spelling nit-picker, I personally have spent more time than I care to admit on arguing the importance of using English as it was intended rather than however is easiest to type.  Then I got some serious criticism from someone from Greece that I wasn't being fair to those
people around the world who are learning English as a second, third, or fourth language.  Quite a shock trying to think of the Internet as a world-wide entity sometimes, really confounds conventions.<P>

 I agree with your assessment of UO2, it looks sickeningly rough at this point.  But there are some things that make it shine, like the texture
maps, some of the buildings, and devotion to movement realism.  I have always
felt that EQ was lacking especially in movement realism, leaving me wonder sometimes how these characters we're playing are so capable of defying physics.  Without running through a whine list, here's a couple of
examples:<P>

 when a character holding a long heavy staff is running the staff axes the air in front of them as though it didn't weigh a thing, it's too bad movements weren't added to change the way your character runs depending on the type of weapon being wielded.  Iksars, while having nice attractive movements and fantastic skeletons, look as though they're constipated when they run and stoned when they walk.  Consequently I try to just stand in
one place and cast spells all the time, it's much easier to watch.  But as far as the UO2 skeletons go, I think they lost their attention to reality
after spending too much time with love-motion capturing and decided not to make the characters look as though they could be biological in nature.  The humans they have used look like elongated elves and the other races (or species, or whatever those are supposed to be) look like walking sticks.
I suppose if they wanted to make the characters look like they were swift
and light they succeeded in a way, but they completely lack any look of power and mass.<P>

 Lastly, do you have any tips for someone hoping to learn to do your job,
or a job like yours?  I've been studying illustration and traditional artwork for a few years now and I'd love to be able to use that in conjunction
with 3D-rendering skills, if I can get them.<P>

 Sincerely,<BR>
 Bill Wiltfong

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   Hi there, Bill.  Okay, firstly, my web site is <a href="http://www.milospace.net/">http://www.milospace.net/</a>
(I get requests for that URL a lot, here -- perhaps it should be posted at
the top of the Ask Milo page).  Thanks for your sympathy regarding my
pet peeve about the poor usage of the English language on the Net.<P>

   Secondly, I appreciate your concurring with my opinion of the current
status of the Ultima Online sequel.  I regret that I can't go into greater
detail about my assessment of it (at least, not to the public at large);
what
I wrote upset quite a few people in this industry, and infuriated a lot of
CRPG players and readers of Harry Knowles-wannabe sites.  As a
result, I have been prudently advised and ordered never again to speak
publicly of the efforts of other game companies in unflattering ways.
Brad McQuaid is a good friend of mine, and I think that I give him
enough heart palpitations every Monday without bringing his associates
and clientele swiftly down upon his head in this manner.<P>

   You can find answers to your last question in the Ask Milo archives.<P>

<HR align="center" width="85%"><P>

 Why the hell do you suck so much? Just wandering. You should also give some people your respect because you seem to like to treat people like crap. LATER.<P>

 GP69GP69

<P> <P><b><i>
<font face="Georgia" size="4" color="#9F3215">
Milo Says:
</font></i></b><BR>

   I give my respect to people who earn it; furthermore, criticizing someone
doesn't mean that I don't respect him/her.  To too many people, showing
respect means smiling and nodding one's head and perhaps even behaving
sycophantically.  I don't know what you call respect, but to me, it's just
the
acknowledgment of worth; I don't see that this comprises acting like a
yes-man all the time.  Heck, I respect only those people who are both
intelligent and secure enough to hear me criticize them, anyway (should I
feel the need to do that).  I certainly *don't* respect whiners and
crybabies, neither will I treat everyone the same, because I like some
people more than others.  Besides, my power to upset someone is only as
strong as the veneration that this person bestows upon me.  Why should
anyone who doesn't know me well enough to value my opinions care what
I have to say about him/her?<P>

   Perhaps, instead of "respect," you should have written "common
courtesy," in which case I would have agreed with you that I can be fairly
uncivil, sometimes.  I'm working on that, but it's not easy, mainly because
people tend to be so easily upset that the line between honesty and
rudeness becomes fine to the point of being invisible.  I have no intention
of compromising my candor, so please, be patient with me.<P>

